Not=
 exactly. Awakening is just a step towards freedom. Freedom comes in the en=
d after walking a path for enough time after awakening.
=C2=A0
An unawakene=
d sadhaka practicing jnana yoga reads books and talks eloquently about how =
everything is god, but looks at different people, objects and experiences w=
ith a different attitude. He becomes happy (if not externally, atleast inte=
rnally) when people praise him and becomes upset when people criticize him,=
 and so on. An awakened sadhaka practicing jnana yoga starts to honestly co=
ntemplate one's actions, words, thoughts (and even instincts finally) and s=
lowly weeds out conditioning that makes one look at different transient thi=
ngs differently. As his equanimity increases, still there will be episodes =
of getting carried away. As he employs contemplation and self-correction mo=
re and more, such episodes will become less and less frequent and one will =
become liberated in the end.
=C2=A0
An unawakened sadhaka practicing karma =
yoga passionately engages in dharmik actions for the benefit of others. He =
gets elated and feels proud when good results come and becomes upset when b=
ad results come. An awakened sadhaka practicing karma yoga starts to have d=
etachment to results. When something happens which makes him elated, proud,=
 ashamed or upset, he will not think much about it, take it as god's prasad=
 and think about what is the right action for him right now. As his detachm=
ent increases, still there will be episodes of getting carried away. As one=
 becomes more and more detached (to results of actions), such episodes will=
 become less and less frequent and one will become liberated in the end.
=
=C2=A0
An unawakened sadhaka practicing raja yoga goes through yama, niyama=
, pratyahara, dhyana, dharana etc. His psychic life force may even arise an=
d ascend. He may have various experiences and may feel proud or become atta=
ched to them. An awakened sadhaka practicing raja yoga will not not lose se=
lf-control in the face of anything and will keep the focus on samadhi. He w=
ill not be distracted by anything that comes on the way and keep perfecting=
 concentration and self-control so that samadhi (deep concentration on the =
unconditioned Self) comes. In the beginning, one may be in samadhi state no=
w and then. As practice is perfected, one can be in it all the time and bec=
ome liberated.
=C2=A0
An unawkened sadhaka practicing bhakti yoga is devote=
d to god and worships him/her as much as one can, but will project his ego,=
 conditioning and desires onto his worship and hence onto the god he worshi=
ps. For example, he may think "I worship the highest god while that person =
worships a lower god. I am better" or "I am worshipping god everyday. I wil=
l get so and so result" or "I worship god more than that person. I am bette=
r". An awkened sadhaka practicing bhakti yoga has little expectation, pride=
 etc. Worship becomes not about him but about god! He worships god and marv=
els at the power that holds this cosmos together - the power that runs thin=
gs infinitismally smaller than a boson and infinitely larger than a galaxy.=
 He will look at himself as a fully insignificant particle in front a supre=
me power. His desires, likes, dislikes, conditioning and agendas start to s=
eem too insignificant in front of contemplating about that supreme power. E=
ven as that
 devotional spirit increases, there will be episodes when one b=
ecomes self-centered in one's worship. But with practice, one loses oneself=
 completely and surrenders completely to the supreme power and become liber=
ated in the end.
=C2=A0
In each path, one may walk the path without making =
any significant progress for a long time. As one starts to imbibe the inher=
ent qualities of the path, some internal transformation will kick in. Yet, =
the force of prior conditioning, coming from many lives, is too strong to o=
vercome. One keeps walking..
